In previous materials we put layout application aside and focus on the really important issue of the application. Unfortunately, in real world appearance of your work is at least as important as its content and performance. Appearance is actually a measure of importance. Letâ€™s review some layouts available in shiny package.

tabsetPanel

One of the comfortable solutions is division of application outputs into tabsets with a little help of tabsetPanel function. Below gif with presentation and code of the application.

tabsetPanel( # this initiate tabsets
  tabPanel(title = "title1", # this creates tab 1 with title1
           ..., ), # here we can place nested layout (sidebarPanel) or widgets, or output...
  tabPanel(title = "title2",  # this creates second tab
           .... - ), # here we can place nested layout (sidebarPanel) or widgets, or output...
)

Example

ui.R

ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("Rental price vs. footage in Warsaw"),
  uiOutput("session_id", style = "position: absolute; top: 2px; right: 2px"),
  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      sliderInput("price_max", "Maximum price [PLN]:",
                  min = 0, max = 5 * 10 ^ 5, value = 5 * 10 ^ 5,
                  step = 2 * 10 ^ 3),
      sliderInput("m2_max", HTML("Maximum footage [m<sup>2</sup>]:"),
                  min = 0, max = 6 * 10 ^ 3, value = 6 * 10 ^ 3, step = 250)
    ),
    mainPanel(
      tabsetPanel(
        tabPanel(
          title = "Table",
          DT::dataTableOutput("tbl")
        ),
        tabPanel(
          title = "Chart",
          plotOutput("plt")
        )
      )
    )
  )
)

server.R

library(DT)
library(tidyverse)
library(shiny)

# PoniÅ¼sze wywoÅ‚anie funkcji pozwala poprawnie identyfikowaÄ‡ polskie znaki
# Za jÄ™zyk w tabeli odpowiada parametr `language` w liÅ›cie opcji
Sys.setlocale(category = "LC_ALL", locale = "pl")

data <- readRDS("data/gumtree_en.rds") %>%
  filter(between(price, 0, 10^4), between(footage, 0, 10^2))

opts <- list(
  language = list(url = "//cdn.datatables.net/plug-ins/1.10.19/i18n/Polish.json"),
  pageLength = 10,
  searchHighlight = TRUE
)

server <- function(input, output, session) {
  selected_data <- reactive({
    data %>% 
      filter(price <= input$price_max & footage <= input$m2_max)
  })
  
  output$tbl <- DT::renderDataTable({
    selected_data() %>% select(-description, -bathrooms, -smokers, -animals, -words_in_desc)
  }, options = opts)
  
  output$plt <- renderPlot({
    selected_data() %>% 
      ggplot(aes(footage, price)) +
      geom_point() +
      xlab(expression("Footage ["*m^2*"]")) +
      ylab("Price [PLN]")
  })
}

Navbar Panel

Alternative for tabsetPanel, more info available here: https://shiny.rstudio.com/gallery/navbar-example.html

conditionalPanel

With this function visibility of the panels can be related to values of certain conditions which depends on input values (hence behaviour of an user).

Function name:

conditionalPanel(condition, ...)

Arguments

condition - condition which depends on input list, written in Java Script language. Key difference (apart from other obvious syntax issues) is that instead of â€œ$â€ symbol â€œ.â€ is used.

... - content of the panel

Example

ui.R

ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("Rental price vs. footage - Warsaw real estate market"),
  uiOutput("session_id", style = "position: absolute; top: 2px; right: 2px"),
  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      width = 2,
      sliderInput("price_max", "Maximum price [PLN]:",
                  min = 0, max = 5 * 10 ^ 5, value = 5 * 10 ^ 5,
                  step = 2 * 10 ^ 3),
      sliderInput("m2_max", HTML("Maximum footage [m<sup>2</sup>]:"),
                  min = 0, max = 6 * 10 ^ 3, value = 6 * 10 ^ 3, step = 250),
      radioButtons("type_chart", "Type of visualisation", choices = c("table", "chart"))
    ),
    mainPanel(
      width = 10,
      conditionalPanel(
        "input.type_chart == 'table'",
        DT::dataTableOutput("tbl")
      ),
      conditionalPanel(
        "input.type_chart == 'chart'",
        plotOutput("plt")
      )
    )
  )
)

Rules of application arrangement in shiny app

If application have a many elements in graphical interface, arrangement of them is often critical for optimising user experience. Placement of elements in web application is called layout. Until know we used one basic type of layout - sidebarLayout in which app was splitted into two panels/parts sidebarfor widgets and main panel for output.

Another layout, much more flexible is grid layout. As name indiates, this function creates a grid of rows and columns, where each is equivalent of panel. For creation of rows and columns functions fluidRow and fluidColumn are responsible. Because webpage have limited only width, we need to remember, that in shiny maximum width (whole width of website) is 12. So 6 itâ€™s a half.

The raw page is initiated with fluidPage(). All in all it is very straightforward. Different layout functions can be mixed (nested) in order to create more complex and fancy layouts, but rememeber this - more simple means better.

Examples are very brief you can test it on any app you like. In place of three dots put any function which returns widget or output from server.

Example 1: fluidPage with grid layout

One row with two columns, proportion of width 1:2.

fluidPage(
  fluidRow(
    column(width = 4, ...),
    column(width = 8, ...)
  )
)

Below two rows, each with two columns with equal width.

fluidPage(
  fluidRow(
    column(width = 6, ...),
    column(width = 6, ...)
  ),
  fluidRow(
    column(width = 6, ...),
    column(width = 6, ...)
  )
)

Row splitted into two columns podzielony na dwie kolumny. Second columns splitted into two rows:

fluidPage(
  fluidRow(
    column(width = 8, â€¦),
    column(width = 4,
      fluidRow(column(width = 12, ...)),
      fluidRow(column(width = 12, ...))
    )
  )
)

Example 2: SibebarPanel with grid layout

In this example we used ukÅ‚ad layout from previous example to create app which displays chart and table in grid layout, but also has sidebar panel with widgets. This example presents how we can combine functionalities of different layout functions. In fact the can be nested.

ui.R

ui <- fluidPage(
  fluidRow(
    column(width = 2, 
           wellPanel(
             sliderInput("price_max", "Maximum price [PLN]:",
                         min = 0, max = 5 * 10 ^ 5, value = 5 * 10 ^ 5,
                         step = 2 * 10 ^ 3),
             sliderInput("m2_max", HTML("Maximum footage [m<sup>2</sup>]:"),
                         min = 0, max = 6 * 10 ^ 3, value = 6 * 10 ^ 3, step = 250)
           )
    ),
    column(width = 8, 
           fluidRow(column(width = 12, DT::dataTableOutput("tbl"))),
           fluidRow(column(width = 12, plotOutput("plt")))
    )
  )
)
